In Kotlin, <code>if</code>, <code>when</code> and <code>try</code> are expressions that return values:

<pre><code>// if as expression
val label = if (delivery.isExpress) "EXPRESS" else "STANDARD"

// when (replaces switch — exhaustive with sealed classes)
val fee = when (delivery.type) {
    DeliveryType.EXPRESS -> 9.99
    DeliveryType.STANDARD -> 4.99
    DeliveryType.PICKUP -> 0.0
}

// try as expression
val port = try {
    config["server.port"].toInt()
} catch (e: NumberFormatException) {
    8080
}</code></pre>

<strong>Why this matters:</strong> Expressions encourage <code>val</code> usage because you can initialize immutable variables from complex logic without intermediate mutable state.

Extension functions are compiled to static methods. The receiver becomes the first parameter:

<pre><code>// Kotlin source
fun String.removeWhitespace(): String = this.replace(" ", "")

// Generated bytecode (decompiled to Java)
public static String removeWhitespace(String $this$removeWhitespace) {
    return $this$removeWhitespace.replace(" ", "");
}</code></pre>

<strong>Important implications:</strong>
• Extensions are resolved statically (no virtual dispatch)
• They cannot access private members of the class
• They cannot override existing members
• They are simply syntactic sugar over static methods

A higher-order function takes a function as parameter or returns one:

<pre><code>// Function parameter
fun <T> List<T>.filterAndLog(
    predicate: (T) -> Boolean,
    logger: (T) -> Unit = {}
): List<T> {
    return filter { item ->
        val matches = predicate(item)
        if (!matches) logger(item)
        matches
    }
}

// Usage
val validDeliveries = deliveries.filterAndLog(
    predicate = { it.weight <= maxWeight },
    logger = { log.warn("Rejected: ${it.id} exceeds weight limit") }
)</code></pre>

<strong>Why this matters:</strong> Higher-order functions enable the Strategy pattern without classes, reduce boilerplate in cross-cutting concerns, and make testing easier through function injection.

Lambda functions in JVM languages create objects. The <code>inline</code> keyword eliminates this overhead:

<pre><code>// Without inline: creates a Function object on every call
fun <T> measure(block: () -> T): T { ... }

// With inline: compiler copies the body at each call site
inline fun <T> measure(block: () -> T): T {
    val start = System.nanoTime()
    val result = block()
    val elapsed = System.nanoTime() - start
    log.debug("Executed in ${elapsed}ns")
    return result
}

// At the call site, no Function object is created
val result = measure { repository.findAll() }</code></pre>

<strong>Production impact:</strong> Kotlin's standard library functions (<code>let</code>, <code>apply</code>, <code>filter</code>, <code>map</code>) are all <code>inline</code>. This means using lambdas in Kotlin typically has zero allocation overhead — unlike Java streams.

To understand Data Classes, it helps to understand the history of Java.

Imagine a very simple object:

<pre><code>public class Customer {
    private Long id;
    private String name;
}</code></pre>

Looks harmless. But in a real application you immediately need:

• constructor
• getters
• setters
• equals()
• hashCode()
• toString()

If the object must be immutable: remove setters, create constructor, implement Builder, maybe implement copy().

A class with two fields easily becomes 70–100 lines long. None of that code expresses business logic. It is infrastructure.

Kotlin asked a simple question: <strong>Why should developers write code that the compiler already knows how to generate?</strong>

That question led to Data Classes.

Instead of writing everything manually:

<pre><code>public class Customer {
    private final Long id;
    private final String name;
    // constructor
    // getters
    // equals
    // hashCode
    // toString
}</code></pre>

Kotlin reduces it to:

<pre><code>data class Customer(
    val id: Long,
    val name: String
)</code></pre>

The compiler performs the repetitive work. This makes code shorter, easier to review, harder to implement incorrectly, and easier to maintain.

Unlike languages that require special runtime support, Data Classes do not exist as a special JVM type. After compilation, they become ordinary Java classes with generated methods.

Consider:

<pre><code>data class Product(
    val id: Long,
    val name: String,
    val price: BigDecimal
)</code></pre>

The compiler expands it into something conceptually similar to:

<pre><code>public final class Product {
    private final long id;
    private final String name;
    private final BigDecimal price;

    public Product(long id, String name, BigDecimal price) { ... }
    public long getId() { return id; }
    public String getName() { return name; }
    public BigDecimal getPrice() { return price; }

    @Override public boolean equals(Object obj) { ... }
    @Override public int hashCode() { ... }
    @Override public String toString() { ... }

    public Product copy(long id, String name, BigDecimal price) {
        return new Product(id, name, price);
    }

    public long component1() { return id; }
    public String component2() { return name; }
    public BigDecimal component3() { return price; }
}</code></pre>

Notice: no special runtime representation. Everything is generated during compilation. This is one reason Kotlin integrates so naturally with existing Java libraries.

Java <code>enum</code> is limited to constant values. Sealed classes allow each variant to carry different data:

<pre><code>// Java enum — each variant must have the same shape
enum DeliveryStatus { PENDING, IN_TRANSIT, DELIVERED, FAILED }
// Cannot attach a reason to FAILED or a driver to IN_TRANSIT

// Kotlin sealed — each variant has its own structure
sealed class DeliveryStatus {
    object Pending : DeliveryStatus()
    data class InTransit(val driver: Driver, val eta: Instant) : DeliveryStatus()
    data class Delivered(val timestamp: Instant, val signature: String?) : DeliveryStatus()
    data class Failed(val reason: String, val retryAt: Instant?) : DeliveryStatus()
}</code></pre>

This is algebraic data types (ADT) on the JVM — a concept from functional programming that Kotlin brings to enterprise development.

When a <code>when</code> expression operates on a sealed class, the compiler verifies all cases are handled:

<pre><code>fun buildTrackingMessage(status: DeliveryStatus): String =
    when (status) {
        is DeliveryStatus.Pending ->
            "Your order is being prepared"
        is DeliveryStatus.InTransit ->
            "Driver ${status.driver.name} — ETA ${status.eta.formatForDisplay()}"
        is DeliveryStatus.Delivered ->
            "Delivered at ${status.timestamp.formatForDisplay()}"
        is DeliveryStatus.Failed ->
            "Delivery failed: ${status.reason}"
        // No else needed — compiler verified all cases
    }

// If you add a new subclass later, every exhaustive when FAILS TO COMPILE
// until you handle the new case. This is a refactoring safety net.</code></pre>

<strong>Production impact:</strong> Adding a new state to the hierarchy causes compile-time failures everywhere that state is not handled. You cannot forget to handle new cases.

Kotlin 1.5+ allows sealed interfaces, which are more flexible because a class can implement multiple interfaces:

<pre><code>sealed interface PaymentResult
sealed interface InventoryResult

data class Success(val id: String) : PaymentResult, InventoryResult
data class Failure(val error: String) : PaymentResult
data class OutOfStock(val sku: String) : InventoryResult

// Useful for modeling results in service layers
fun processOrder(order: Order): PaymentResult = when {
    order.amount <= 0 -> Failure("Invalid amount")
    else -> chargeCard(order)
}</code></pre>

Prefer sealed interfaces when you need a type that can participate in multiple hierarchies.

Sealed classes shine in domain modeling. Common production use cases:

• <strong>Result types:</strong> <code>sealed class Result&lt;T&gt;</code> with <code>Success(data: T)</code> and <code>Failure(error: Throwable)</code>
• <strong>State machines:</strong> each sealed subclass represents a valid state with its specific data
• <strong>Event hierarchies:</strong> domain events where each type carries different payload
• <strong>UI states:</strong> Loading, Content, Error with different fields per state

<pre><code>// Better than nullable returns or exception-driven control flow
sealed class RouteResult {
    data class Found(val route: Route) : RouteResult()
    data class NoDriverAvailable(val estimatedWait: Duration) : RouteResult()
    data class ServiceAreaUnavailable(val reason: String) : RouteResult()
}

fun assignRoute(delivery: Delivery): RouteResult { ... }

// All three outcomes must be handled explicitly at every call site
when (val result = assignRoute(delivery)) {
    is RouteResult.Found -> dispatch(result.route)
    is RouteResult.NoDriverAvailable -> scheduleRetry(result.estimatedWait)
    is RouteResult.ServiceAreaUnavailable -> notifyCustomer(result.reason)
}</code></pre>

An object declaration creates a thread-safe singleton initialized lazily on first access:

<pre><code>// Singleton — initialized once, thread-safe by the JVM class loader
object RouteCache {
    private val cache = ConcurrentHashMap<String, Route>()

    fun get(key: String): Route? = cache[key]
    fun put(key: String, route: Route) { cache[key] = route }
    fun invalidate() = cache.clear()
}

// Usage — no instantiation, accessed by name
RouteCache.put("WH-A-Store-42", computedRoute)
val route = RouteCache.get("WH-A-Store-42")
</code></pre>

<strong>Internally:</strong> compiled as a Java class with a <code>public static final INSTANCE</code> field. The JVM guarantees thread-safe initialization via class loading.

Kotlin has no <code>static</code> keyword. Companion objects provide the equivalent:

<pre><code>class Delivery private constructor(
    val id: String,
    val items: List<Item>
) {
    companion object {
        // Factory method pattern
        fun create(items: List<Item>): Delivery {
            require(items.isNotEmpty()) { "Delivery must have at least one item" }
            return Delivery(
                id = generateId(),
                items = items
            )
        }

        // Constants
        const val MAX_WEIGHT_KG = 50.0
        private val ID_PREFIX = "DEL"

        private fun generateId() = "$ID_PREFIX-${UUID.randomUUID()}"
    }
}

// Usage
val delivery = Delivery.create(items)  // looks like a static factory
println(Delivery.MAX_WEIGHT_KG)        // looks like a static constant</code></pre>

<strong>@JvmStatic annotation:</strong> When Java code needs to call a companion member as a true static method, annotate with <code>@JvmStatic</code>.

Object expressions replace Java anonymous classes:

<pre><code>// Java anonymous class equivalent
val comparator = object : Comparator<Delivery> {
    override fun compare(a: Delivery, b: Delivery): Int =
        a.estimatedArrival.compareTo(b.estimatedArrival)
}

// More commonly: anonymous objects implementing interfaces on the fly
val listener = object : DeliveryEventListener {
    override fun onDispatched(event: DispatchedEvent) {
        log.info("Dispatched: ${event.deliveryId}")
    }
    override fun onDelivered(event: DeliveredEvent) {
        metrics.increment("deliveries.completed")
    }
}

// Note: unlike Java, Kotlin anonymous objects can capture mutable variables
var count = 0
val counter = object : EventListener {
    override fun onEvent() { count++ }  // captures mutable var — allowed
}</code></pre>

• Putting business logic in object declarations — use them for stateless utilities or registries only
• Overusing companion objects as Java-style utility classes — extension functions are often cleaner
• Not annotating companion members with <code>@JvmStatic</code> when Java interop is needed
• Using object expressions where a lambda suffices (unnecessary verbosity)

<pre><code>// ❌ Verbose — object expression where lambda suffices
deliveries.sortWith(object : Comparator<Delivery> {
    override fun compare(a: Delivery, b: Delivery) = a.id.compareTo(b.id)
})

// ✅ Concise — lambda for SAM interfaces
deliveries.sortWith { a, b -> a.id.compareTo(b.id) }
// Or even simpler
deliveries.sortBy { it.id }</code></pre>

Java's variance is use-site (<code>? extends T</code>, <code>? super T</code>). Kotlin adds declaration-site variance:

<pre><code>// out — covariant (producer). Can only produce T, not consume it.
// A Producer<Dog> IS a Producer<Animal>
interface Producer<out T> {
    fun produce(): T  // OK — returns T
    // fun consume(value: T)  // COMPILATION ERROR — cannot take T as input
}

// in — contravariant (consumer). Can only consume T, not produce it.
// A Consumer<Animal> IS a Consumer<Dog>
interface Consumer<in T> {
    fun consume(value: T)  // OK — takes T as input
    // fun produce(): T    // COMPILATION ERROR — cannot return T
}

// Practical example with standard library
// List<out T> — covariant. A List<Dog> can be used where List<Animal> is expected
val dogs: List<Dog> = listOf(Dog(), Dog())
val animals: List<Animal> = dogs  // OK — List is covariant (out T)

// MutableList<T> — invariant. Cannot assign MutableList<Dog> to MutableList<Animal>
val mutableDogs: MutableList<Dog> = mutableListOf()
// val mutableAnimals: MutableList<Animal> = mutableDogs  // COMPILE ERROR</code></pre>

<strong>Memory rule:</strong> <code>out</code> = producer = can be assigned to supertype variable. <code>in</code> = consumer = can be assigned to subtype variable.

Java erases generic types at runtime (type erasure). Kotlin's <code>reified</code> keyword, used with <code>inline</code> functions, preserves the type:

<pre><code>// Java generic — type erased at runtime
fun <T> parseJson(json: String): T {
    // Cannot do: T::class.java — T is erased!
    return objectMapper.readValue(json, ???)
}

// Kotlin reified — type available at runtime
inline fun <reified T> parseJson(json: String): T =
    objectMapper.readValue(json, T::class.java)  // T is a real class here!

// Usage — no Class<T> parameter needed!
val delivery: Delivery = parseJson(jsonString)
val events: List<Event> = parseJson(jsonString)

// Another common use: type-safe event filtering
inline fun <reified T : DomainEvent> EventBus.subscribe(
    crossinline handler: (T) -> Unit
) {
    subscribe(T::class) { event ->
        if (event is T) handler(event)
    }
}

// Usage — clean, no class token needed
eventBus.subscribe<DeliveryCompletedEvent> { event ->
    updateMetrics(event)
}</code></pre>

<strong>Key rule:</strong> <code>reified</code> only works with <code>inline</code> functions. The compiler copies the function body at each call site, substituting the actual type.

Delegated properties let you reuse property access logic across many properties:

<pre><code>// lazy — computed once on first access, thread-safe by default
class RouteOptimizer {
    val graph: Graph by lazy {
        // Expensive computation — runs only when first accessed
        buildFullRouteGraph()
    }
}

// observable — notified on every change
class OrderStatus {
    var status: String by Delegates.observable("PENDING") { _, old, new ->
        log.info("Status changed: $old -> $new")
        eventBus.publish(StatusChangedEvent(old, new))
    }
}

// vetoable — can reject a change
var weight: Double by Delegates.vetoable(0.0) { _, _, new ->
    new >= 0.0  // reject negative weights
}

// notNull — like lateinit but for nullable types
var config: AppConfig by Delegates.notNull()  // throws if accessed before assignment</code></pre>

Properties can delegate to a <code>Map</code>, which is useful for configuration objects and deserializing dynamic data:

<pre><code>class ServiceConfig(private val properties: Map<String, Any>) {
    val host: String by properties
    val port: Int by properties
    val timeout: Int by properties
}

val config = ServiceConfig(mapOf(
    "host" to "localhost",
    "port" to 8080,
    "timeout" to 30
))

println(config.host)  // delegates to properties["host"]

// Mutable version with MutableMap
class MutableConfig(private val props: MutableMap<String, Any> = mutableMapOf()) {
    var debug: Boolean by props
}

val cfg = MutableConfig()
cfg.debug = true
println(cfg.props)  // {"debug": true}</code></pre>

A regular <code>Flow</code> is cold: the producer code runs only when a collector starts collecting.

<pre><code>import kotlinx.coroutines.flow.*

// Building a flow — nothing executes yet
fun deliveryUpdates(orderId: String): Flow<DeliveryEvent> = flow {
    while (true) {
        val event = repository.getLatestEvent(orderId)
        emit(event)          // suspends until collected
        delay(5_000)         // wait 5 seconds before next poll
    }
}

// Collecting — this is where execution starts
suspend fun trackDelivery(orderId: String) {
    deliveryUpdates(orderId)
        .filter { it.isStatusChange() }
        .collect { event ->
            println("Status: ${event.status}")
        }
}

// Each call to collect() restarts the flow from scratch
// Two collectors = two independent streams = producer runs twice</code></pre>

<strong>Key insight:</strong> Cold = no shared state between collectors. Every collector gets its own independent stream.

Hot flows emit regardless of whether anyone is collecting:

<pre><code>// StateFlow — holds a current state value, like LiveData
// Always has a value, replays the latest to new collectors
class DeliveryViewModel {
    private val _state = MutableStateFlow<DeliveryState>(DeliveryState.Loading)
    val state: StateFlow<DeliveryState> = _state.asStateFlow()

    fun loadDelivery(id: String) {
        viewModelScope.launch {
            _state.value = DeliveryState.Loading
            try {
                val delivery = repository.find(id)
                _state.value = DeliveryState.Success(delivery)
            } catch (e: Exception) {
                _state.value = DeliveryState.Error(e.message)
            }
        }
    }
}

// SharedFlow — event bus, configurable replay and buffer
class EventBus {
    private val _events = MutableSharedFlow<DomainEvent>(
        replay = 0,          // new subscribers don't get past events
        extraBufferCapacity = 64
    )
    val events: SharedFlow<DomainEvent> = _events.asSharedFlow()

    suspend fun publish(event: DomainEvent) = _events.emit(event)
}

// Collecting StateFlow — in coroutine scope
scope.launch {
    viewModel.state
        .collect { state -> render(state) }
}</code></pre>

<strong>Decision:</strong> Use <code>StateFlow</code> for state (has current value). Use <code>SharedFlow</code> for events (fire-and-forget, no current value).

Without <code>@DslMarker</code>, nested DSL blocks can accidentally call methods from outer receivers:

<pre><code>// Potential confusion without @DslMarker:
route("Test") {
    stop("WH-A", "Address") {
        stop("WH-B", "inner")  // !! This calls the OUTER route's stop(), not a stop's sub-method!
    }
}

// Solution: mark the DSL with a custom annotation
@DslMarker
annotation class RouteDsl

@RouteDsl
class RouteBuilder { ... }

@RouteDsl
class StopBuilder { ... }

// Now the compiler prevents calling outer DSL methods from inner scopes
// This is how Gradle and kotlinx.html prevent scope leakage</code></pre>

DSLs are not just academic — they appear in real production code:

<pre><code>// Spring Security DSL (Kotlin-idiomatic config)
http {
    authorizeHttpRequests {
        authorize("/api/public/**", permitAll)
        authorize("/api/deliveries/**", hasRole("DRIVER"))
        authorize(anyRequest, authenticated)
    }
    csrf { disable() }
    sessionManagement { stateless() }
}

// Ktor routing DSL
routing {
    route("/api/deliveries") {
        get { call.respond(deliveryService.getAll()) }
        post { val dto = call.receive<DeliveryDTO>(); call.respond(deliveryService.create(dto)) }
        route("/{id}") {
            get { call.respond(deliveryService.get(call.parameters["id"]!!)) }
            delete { deliveryService.delete(call.parameters["id"]!!); call.respond(HttpStatusCode.NoContent) }
        }
    }
}

// Test DSL for readable assertions
assertDelivery(result) {
    hasStatus(DeliveryStatus.InTransit)
    driver { hasName("Klaus") }
    eta { isWithin(minutes = 30) }
}</code></pre>

Knowing how to read and write DSLs makes you effective with the Kotlin ecosystem. Knowing the mechanism (lambda with receiver + builder pattern) demonstrates deep language understanding.

Traditional concurrent code on the JVM uses threads. Threads are expensive: each consumes ~1MB of stack memory and the OS must context-switch between them. A server with 10,000 simultaneous I/O-bound operations would need 10,000 threads — impractical.

The traditional alternatives — callbacks and reactive streams — solve the resource problem but introduce different problems: callback hell, complex error propagation, and code that looks nothing like the sequential logic it implements.

<strong>Coroutines offer a third path:</strong> write sequential-looking code that suspends (not blocks) while waiting for I/O, freeing the underlying thread for other work. The overhead per coroutine is ~1KB vs ~1MB for a thread.

<pre><code>// ❌ Callback-based — inverted logic, error handling scattered
fun dispatchDelivery(id: String) {
    fetchDelivery(id) { delivery ->
        fetchRoute(delivery.routeId) { route ->
            assignDriver(route) { driver ->
                notify(driver, delivery) { result ->
                    handleResult(result) // 4 levels of nesting for linear logic
                }
            }
        }
    }
}

// ✅ Coroutine — sequential logic, automatic suspension
suspend fun dispatchDelivery(id: String) {
    val delivery = fetchDelivery(id)        // suspends, not blocks
    val route    = fetchRoute(delivery.routeId)
    val driver   = assignDriver(route)
    val result   = notify(driver, delivery)
    handleResult(result)
}</code></pre>

A <code>suspend</code> function can pause its execution without blocking the underlying thread. Other coroutines can use the same thread while this one waits.

<pre><code>// suspend function — can only be called from another suspend function or a coroutine builder
suspend fun fetchDelivery(id: String): Delivery {
    return withContext(Dispatchers.IO) { // suspend and switch to IO thread pool
        deliveryRepository.findById(id)
    }
}

// Regular function — cannot call suspend directly
fun regularFun() {
    fetchDelivery("123") // COMPILATION ERROR — must be in coroutine or suspend context
}

// Key principle: suspension is cooperative — the function voluntarily suspends at
// specific points (withContext, delay, await) rather than being preempted by the OS

// Under the hood — the compiler transforms suspend functions into state machines:
// suspend fun example() { val a = step1(); val b = step2(a); return b }
// becomes roughly:
// fun example(continuation: Continuation): Any {
//   when (continuation.label) {
//     0 -> { continuation.label = 1; return step1(continuation) }
//     1 -> { val a = continuation.result; continuation.label = 2; return step2(a, continuation) }
//     2 -> { return continuation.result }
//   }
// }</code></pre>

Coroutines are always launched within a <strong>CoroutineScope</strong>. The scope determines the lifecycle — when the scope is cancelled, all coroutines within it are cancelled.

<pre><code>import kotlinx.coroutines.*

// launch — fire and forget (returns Job)
fun startDispatchJob(scope: CoroutineScope, deliveryId: String) {
    scope.launch {
        processDelivery(deliveryId) // runs concurrently, result ignored
    }
}

// async — concurrent with result (returns Deferred)
suspend fun dispatchConcurrently(deliveryId: String): DispatchResult {
    return coroutineScope { // structured scope — waits for all children
        val routeDeferred  = async { fetchRoute(deliveryId) }
        val driverDeferred = async { findAvailableDriver(deliveryId) }
        val route  = routeDeferred.await()
        val driver = driverDeferred.await()
        DispatchResult(route, driver)
    } // coroutineScope returns only when both async blocks complete
}

// runBlocking — bridges blocking code with coroutines (tests and main())
fun main() = runBlocking {
    val result = dispatchConcurrently("DEL-001")
    println(result)
}

// ❌ GlobalScope — never use in production
GlobalScope.launch { ... } // Unstructured — lifecycle uncontrolled, leaks on cancellation</code></pre>

<strong>Rule:</strong> Never use GlobalScope. Always use a structured scope (viewModelScope, lifecycleScope, coroutineScope, or a custom scope with a clear lifecycle).

Structured concurrency is the core design principle of Kotlin coroutines. It enforces a parent-child relationship between coroutines: <strong>a parent does not complete until all its children complete</strong>, and <strong>if a parent is cancelled, all children are cancelled</strong>.

<pre><code>suspend fun processDeliveries(ids: List&lt;String&gt;): List&lt;DeliveryResult&gt; {
    return coroutineScope { // NEW scope — creates a structured boundary
        ids.map { id ->
            async { processDelivery(id) } // child coroutines
        }.awaitAll() // wait for ALL children
    } // coroutineScope completes only when all async children complete
    // If ONE child throws, the scope cancels ALL other children automatically
}

// Comparison — without structured concurrency:
fun badExample(ids: List&lt;String&gt;): List&lt;Job&gt; {
    return ids.map { id ->
        GlobalScope.launch { processDelivery(id) } // Uncontrolled!
        // If one fails, others keep running — no cleanup
        // How do you cancel them? How do you know when they're done?
    }
}

// Cancellation propagates hierarchically:
val parentJob = scope.launch {
    launch { longRunningTask1() }  // child 1
    launch { longRunningTask2() }  // child 2
}
parentJob.cancel() // Cancels parent AND both children automatically</code></pre>

<strong>Why structured concurrency matters in production:</strong>
• No orphaned coroutines consuming resources after a request completes
• Errors propagate to the logical owner, not lost in the void
• Cancellation is cooperative but systematic — no manual cleanup needed
• Testing is easier — coroutines complete before assertions

A Dispatcher determines which thread or thread pool executes a coroutine. Choosing the wrong dispatcher causes either thread starvation or wasted resources.

<pre><code>// Dispatchers.Default — CPU-bound work (uses CPU-core threads)
suspend fun calculateOptimalRoute(stops: List&lt;Location&gt;): Route {
    return withContext(Dispatchers.Default) {
        routeOptimizer.compute(stops) // CPU-intensive algorithm
    }
}

// Dispatchers.IO — I/O-bound work (expandable pool, up to 64 threads by default)
suspend fun fetchDelivery(id: String): Delivery {
    return withContext(Dispatchers.IO) {
        deliveryRepository.findById(id) // blocking JDBC call
    }
}

// Dispatchers.Main — UI thread (Android/Compose — not relevant for backend)

// Dispatchers.Unconfined — inherits caller context, avoid in production

// Custom dispatcher for fine-grained control
val dbDispatcher = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(5).asCoroutineDispatcher()
suspend fun heavyBatchQuery(): List&lt;Delivery&gt; {
    return withContext(dbDispatcher) {
        deliveryRepository.findAll() // dedicated pool, won't exhaust IO dispatcher
    }
}

// withContext switches dispatcher without creating a new coroutine
suspend fun orchestrate(id: String): DispatchPlan {
    val delivery = withContext(Dispatchers.IO) { fetch(id) }       // IO
    val route    = withContext(Dispatchers.Default) { compute(delivery) } // CPU
    return DispatchPlan(delivery, route)
}</code></pre>

<strong>Rule of thumb:</strong>
• Blocking JDBC, HTTP client, file I/O → Dispatchers.IO
• CPU algorithms, data transformation → Dispatchers.Default
• Mixing both → withContext per section

Coroutine exception handling is different from regular try/catch because of the parent-child scope structure.

<pre><code>// launch — exceptions are delivered to the parent scope (or CoroutineExceptionHandler)
val handler = CoroutineExceptionHandler { _, ex ->
    logger.error("Unhandled coroutine exception", ex)
}
scope.launch(handler) {
    riskyOperation() // exception goes to handler, not caller
}

// async — exceptions are held in the Deferred, thrown only on .await()
val deferred = scope.async {
    riskyOperation() // exception stored here
}
try {
    val result = deferred.await() // exception thrown HERE
} catch (e: Exception) {
    logger.error("Failed", e)
}

// SupervisorJob — failure in one child does NOT cancel siblings
val supervisorScope = CoroutineScope(SupervisorJob() + Dispatchers.IO)
supervisorScope.launch {
    launch { fetchWeather() }    // fails
    launch { fetchTraffic() }    // still runs! (supervisor)
    launch { fetchRoute() }      // still runs!
}

// supervisorScope builder — local supervisor scope
suspend fun fetchAllData(id: String): CombinedData {
    return supervisorScope {
        val weather = async { fetchWeather(id).getOrNull() }  // nullable on fail
        val traffic = async { fetchTraffic(id).getOrNull() }
        val route   = async { fetchRoute(id) }  // mandatory — propagates on fail
        CombinedData(route.await(), weather.await(), traffic.await())
    }
}

// CancellationException is special — never catch and swallow it
try {
    suspendFunction()
} catch (e: CancellationException) {
    throw e // Always re-throw! It is how structured cancellation propagates
} catch (e: Exception) {
    handleError(e)
}</code></pre>

When Kotlin calls Java code without nullability annotations, it sees "platform types" (<code>T!</code>):

<pre><code>// Java: no nullability annotation
public class OrderService {
    public String getOrderId() { ... }  // May return null?
}

// Kotlin: getOrderId() returns String! (platform type)
val service = OrderService()
val id = service.getOrderId()  // String! — may be null at runtime!
val upper = id.toUpperCase()   // Compiles! But may throw NPE!

// Safe approaches:
val id: String = service.getOrderId()   // Fail-fast: NPE immediately if null
val id: String? = service.getOrderId()  // Safe: must handle null explicitly

// Best approach: annotate the Java source
// Add @NonNull / @Nullable (Spring, JetBrains, or JSR-305)
public @NonNull String getOrderId() { ... }  // Kotlin now sees String (non-null)

// If you cannot modify the Java code: wrap at the boundary
fun safeGetOrderId(): String = service.getOrderId()
    ?: throw IllegalStateException("OrderService returned null ID")
</code></pre>

<strong>Rule:</strong> Always declare an explicit type when calling Java code. Don't let platform types propagate into your Kotlin code.

At REWE/TRAB, you may work in a mixed Java+Kotlin codebase. Practical migration advice:

<pre><code>// 1. Start with new files in Kotlin — don't rewrite existing Java
// 2. Annotate Java boundaries with @NonNull/@Nullable
// 3. Create Kotlin extension files alongside Java classes
//    (JavaClass+extensions.kt — idiomatic naming)
// 4. Migrate data/DTO classes first — they benefit most and are safest
// 5. Then migrate business logic — use companion objects for factory methods
// 6. Leave framework-heavy classes (Spring controllers with complex annotations) for later

// Common pitfall: Kotlin data class with Java Jackson (needs no-arg constructor)
// Solution: jackson-module-kotlin dependency
@JsonAutoDetect
data class DeliveryDTO(
    val id: String,
    val status: String
