// With jackson-module-kotlin registered, this works fine

// Another pitfall: Kotlin collections are not java.util.List directly
fun javaMethod(list: java.util.List<String>) { ... }
// Kotlin's List<String> IS a java.util.List at runtime — no conversion needed</code></pre>

<strong>Interview tip:</strong> When asked about Java interop, mention platform types as the most dangerous footgun, and <code>@JvmStatic</code>/<code>@JvmOverloads</code> as the most commonly needed annotations.

Spring creates proxies for beans annotated with <code>@Service</code>, <code>@Component</code>, etc. Proxies require subclassing. But Kotlin classes are <code>final</code> by default.

<pre><code>// Without the plugin — Spring cannot proxy this class!
@Service
class DeliveryService { ... }  // final — cannot be subclassed by CGLIB proxy

// With kotlin-spring plugin in build.gradle.kts:
plugins {
    kotlin("plugin.spring")  // makes @Component, @Service, @Repository, etc. non-final
}

// Now Spring can create proxies transparently
// The plugin adds 'open' to classes annotated with Spring stereotypes
// Your source code remains unchanged — just declare the plugin

// What the plugin opens automatically:
// @Component, @Async, @Transactional, @Cacheable,
// @SpringBootTest, and all Spring meta-annotations</code></pre>

<strong>Without this plugin:</strong> Spring silently falls back to JDK dynamic proxies (interface-based) or fails with a <code>BeanCreationException</code>. This is the #1 Kotlin+Spring gotcha.

Every lambda in Java/Kotlin creates a Function object on the heap. For hot paths called millions of times, this adds GC pressure:

<pre><code>// Without inline — creates a Function0 object every call
fun <T> withTiming(block: () -> T): T {
    val start = System.nanoTime()
    return block().also {
        log.debug("Elapsed: ${System.nanoTime() - start}ns")
    }
}

// With inline — the compiler copies the body to each call site
inline fun <T> withTiming(block: () -> T): T {
    val start = System.nanoTime()
    return block().also {
        log.debug("Elapsed: ${System.nanoTime() - start}ns")
    }
}

// Call site — with inline, expands to:
val result = withTiming { repository.findAll() }
// becomes roughly:
val start = System.nanoTime()
val result = repository.findAll()
log.debug("Elapsed: ${System.nanoTime() - start}ns")
// No Function object, no allocation</code></pre>

<strong>The entire Kotlin stdlib is inline</strong>: <code>filter</code>, <code>map</code>, <code>let</code>, <code>apply</code>, <code>run</code>, <code>also</code>, <code>use</code>. This means Kotlin's idiomatic style has zero extra allocation cost for these operations.

<strong>noinline / crossinline:</strong> Within an inline function, use <code>noinline</code> to keep a specific lambda as an object (when it needs to be stored or passed elsewhere), and <code>crossinline</code> when the lambda may be called in a different context.

For a backend service at REWE/TRAB, the real performance concerns are:

1. <strong>Database queries</strong> — N+1, missing indexes, full table scans
2. <strong>Serialization</strong> — Jackson reflection overhead (use streaming for large payloads)
3. <strong>Coroutine context switching</strong> — excessive <code>withContext</code> calls
4. <strong>Collection pipeline size</strong> — use sequences for 1000+ element transformations

Kotlin-specific concerns that rarely matter in practice:
• Lambda allocation (solved by inline stdlib)
• Nullable primitive boxing (avoid in known hot paths)
• String concatenation (use buildString or templates)

