Key points to make:

• <strong>Null safety at the type system level</strong> — NPE is the most common production exception in Java. Kotlin makes nullable explicit, moving bugs from runtime to compile time.

• <strong>Immutability by default</strong> — <code>val</code>, read-only collections, and data classes encourage designs that are naturally thread-safe and easier to reason about.

• <strong>Coroutines for concurrency</strong> — structured concurrency with readable sequential code, without callback hell or reactive learning curve.

• <strong>Expressiveness without magic</strong> — data classes, sealed classes, and extension functions reduce boilerplate. Unlike Lombok, the language handles it natively.

• <strong>100% Java interoperability</strong> — gradual migration is possible. No big-bang rewrite needed.

These topics separate senior Kotlin engineers from intermediate ones:

<strong>Variance (in/out):</strong> Explain declaration-site vs use-site variance, why <code>List</code> is covariant (<code>out T</code>) but <code>MutableList</code> is invariant, and how this prevents type-unsafe operations.

<strong>Reified generics:</strong> Explain type erasure on the JVM, why Kotlin's <code>inline + reified</code> solves it for inline functions, and how to use it to eliminate <code>Class&lt;T&gt;</code> parameters.

<strong>Structured concurrency:</strong> Explain why <code>GlobalScope</code> is dangerous (leaks), what a coroutine scope is, and how <code>SupervisorJob</code> differs from a regular <code>Job</code> (child failure doesn't cancel siblings).

<strong>Flow vs suspend:</strong> Know when to use a suspend function (single value, request-response) vs Flow (multiple values, stream). Know the difference between cold Flow, StateFlow, and SharedFlow.

<strong>Value classes:</strong> Explain how they eliminate the primitive obsession smell while adding zero runtime overhead (except when used as generic type arguments).

